      <i>March’s stock market fall was a glimpse of what might happen if China’s trade relations with the rest of the world collapsed.
</i>
    </mj-text>
    <mj-text color="#212b35" font-weight="bold" font-size="20px">
      “Tough on China”: Clash of Civilizations or Political Tool?

    </mj-text>
    <mj-text color="#212b35" font-size="12px" height=15px font-weight="bold">
      Michael Zhang ’21, Opinions Editor

    </mj-text>
    <mj-text color="#637381" font-size="16px">
      As November approaches, all eyes are on the Presidential election and, more specifically, how Democratic nominee Joe Biden and President Trump will address the novel Coronavirus. COVID-19 has both broken and widened existing fissures within the American societal scheme. While most of our economy lies in shambles, the nation’s wealthiest corporations—Amazon, Google, and Apple—enjoy growth. Mental health distress and rates of suicide have skyrocketed. Disproportionate suffering of Blacks and Hispanics as well as widespread acts of police brutality underscore entrenched racial discrimination. America is hurting.

    </mj-text>
